00:02:55,755 --> 00:02:57,978
[SPEAKER_06]: 23-455 offered by President Morrell and Vice President Behrs.

59
00:02:58,658 --> 00:03:03,944
[SPEAKER_06]: Be it resolved by the Medford City Council that we recognize and celebrate International Human Rights Day on December 10th, 2023.

60
00:03:05,406 --> 00:03:10,190
[SPEAKER_06]: the 75th anniversary of the adoption of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights by the United Nations.

61
00:03:10,710 --> 00:03:14,893
[SPEAKER_06]: Be it further resolved that the Council adopts the following statement made by the Medford Human Rights Commission.

62
00:03:15,493 --> 00:03:17,975
[SPEAKER_06]: Statement in support of International Human Rights Day.

63
00:03:18,476 --> 00:03:24,160
[SPEAKER_06]: The Medford Human Rights Commission recognizes and celebrates International Human Rights Day on December 10th, 2023.

64
00:03:24,780 --> 00:03:29,644
[SPEAKER_06]: On this day 75 years ago, the Universal Declaration of Human Rights was adopted by the United Nations.

65
00:03:30,182 --> 00:03:38,450
[SPEAKER_06]: The document, which consists of a preamble and 30 articles, outlines the fundamental human rights and freedoms to which all of us everywhere around the world are entitled.

66
00:03:39,010 --> 00:03:51,421
[SPEAKER_06]: Its pledge to promote human rights without distinction of nationality, place of residence, gender, national or ethnic origin, religion, language, or any other status is consistent with the principles that established the Medford Human Rights Commission in 2014.

67
00:03:51,461 --> 00:03:51,882
[SPEAKER_06]: The Medford

68
00:03:53,658 --> 00:04:04,422
[SPEAKER_06]: Ordinance expands the rights to include sexual orientation, gender identity, disability, veteran status, or status as a person who is a recipient of federal, state, or local housing subsidies, among others.

69
00:04:05,582 --> 00:04:10,504
[SPEAKER_06]: The 2023 theme of the International Human Rights Day is dignity, freedom, and justice for all.

70
00:04:10,924 --> 00:04:23,168
[SPEAKER_06]: It highlights the equal dignity and worth of every person, the need for a blueprint for sustainable development, the inspiration for stronger human rights protections, and the recognition of human rights as a solution to today's greatest crises.

71
00:04:23,755 --> 00:04:38,401
[SPEAKER_06]: The framework is in alignment with our mission to protect the civil rights of the people of Medford, reinforce a positive community atmosphere, work with community groups and agencies to educate, promote understanding, to eliminate prejudice and intolerance, to mediate within the community wherever needed.

72
00:04:38,421 --> 00:04:40,202
[SPEAKER_06]: The Human Rights Commission embraces diversity.

73
00:04:40,668 --> 00:04:47,591
[SPEAKER_06]: and a culture of respect across differences to ensure that everyone who lives and works in or passes through the city of Medford has an equal opportunity to thrive.

74
00:04:48,311 --> 00:04:57,015
[SPEAKER_06]: Respectfully submitted, Chief Jack Buckley, Stephanie Cornell, Maureen Curley, Immaculate Deluxe, Rob Klein, Diane McDonald, members of the Medford Human Rights Commission.

75
00:04:57,736 --> 00:05:00,417
[SPEAKER_06]: So I want to thank the Human Rights Commission for delivering this

76
00:05:04,992 --> 00:05:05,792
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you, Madam President.

77
00:05:06,733 --> 00:05:20,422
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you for co-sponsoring this resolution with me, and I especially want to thank the members of the Human Rights Commission for both making this statement and asking us to consider it as part of our agenda this evening.

78
00:05:22,782 --> 00:05:33,410
[SPEAKER_19]: I think the statement really speaks for itself, but there was a reason 75 years ago that every country in the world came together to create the United Nations than to declare that human rights are universal value.

79
00:05:33,890 --> 00:05:38,314
[SPEAKER_19]: And that's because for the 40 years before that, they very clearly had not been.

80
00:05:39,615 --> 00:05:46,039
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think we see today, with rising violence and death across the world and wars, a need

81
00:05:48,885 --> 00:05:54,258
[SPEAKER_19]: reaffirm that resolution because just the amount

82
00:05:55,762 --> 00:06:01,243
[SPEAKER_19]: The whole idea of the United Nations, the whole idea of the peace after World War II is that we weren't going to do that again.

83
00:06:01,523 --> 00:06:05,524
[SPEAKER_19]: We weren't going to have millions of people across the world dying because of their identity.

84
00:06:05,644 --> 00:06:11,805
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think we are seeing in many parts of the world today a retrenchment of that.

85
00:06:12,285 --> 00:06:18,307
[SPEAKER_19]: And the answer to that is to reaffirm the universal value of human dignity and freedom and justice.

86
00:06:18,547 --> 00:06:23,428
[SPEAKER_19]: And whatever small part this city can play in that, I think it's an important one.

87
00:06:23,688 --> 00:06:23,948
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

88
00:06:26,505 --> 00:06:27,145
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you so much.

89
00:06:27,666 --> 00:06:41,936
[SPEAKER_17]: I wanted to thank you and Vice President Behrs for introducing this resolution and to especially thank the Human Rights Commission for their hard work of drafting the language of it and sending it to us to be adopted.

90
00:06:43,657 --> 00:06:47,760
[SPEAKER_17]: Very similar to what Vice President Behrs was saying, there's

91
00:06:49,667 --> 00:06:52,608
[SPEAKER_17]: Human rights is something that I think oftentimes we take for granted.

92
00:06:52,888 --> 00:07:00,129
[SPEAKER_17]: Oftentimes we see it on the TV screen as something being talked about in a country so far away.

93
00:07:00,549 --> 00:07:09,031
[SPEAKER_17]: But I think we forget that so many of our community immigrated from countries, left countries, because their human rights were being violated.

94
00:07:09,151 --> 00:07:16,453
[SPEAKER_17]: So many of them came to America, came to Medford for a better future, a future where they can live freely and in dignity.

95
00:07:18,736 --> 00:07:28,386
[SPEAKER_17]: In that, we forget that even though so many have left those countries, they still are connected to those countries.

96
00:07:28,486 --> 00:07:37,034
[SPEAKER_17]: And by connection, we as Medford residents, as the city of Medford, are connected to all these injustices around the world as well.

97
00:07:38,115 --> 00:07:41,178
[SPEAKER_17]: We also forget that civil rights and human rights

98
00:07:41,777 --> 00:07:52,370
[SPEAKER_17]: are at the core of what it means to be an American, what it means to be proud of this country and the values that we fight for and that so many have given their lives for.

99
00:07:53,391 --> 00:07:59,658
[SPEAKER_17]: And in that spirit, you know, we need to be continuously self-critical and continuously

100
00:08:01,532 --> 00:08:04,574
[SPEAKER_17]: protective of human rights here and civil rights here at home.

101
00:08:05,254 --> 00:08:09,076
[SPEAKER_17]: Um, and so I'm, um, really thankful.

102
00:08:09,536 --> 00:08:23,963
[SPEAKER_17]: Um, I know Thanksgiving is passed, but I'm really thankful to the Medford human rights commission for, for drafting this and for putting a spotlight on the work of the commission and the work of our city and to re to frame this in the local sense as well.

103
00:08:24,103 --> 00:08:24,844
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm really grateful.

104
00:08:25,564 --> 00:08:27,925
[SPEAKER_17]: Um, and I'll pass it on to my fellow counselors.

105
00:08:28,265 --> 00:08:28,566
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

106
00:08:28,586 --> 00:08:29,146
[SPEAKER_06]: Councillor Collins.

107
00:08:31,171 --> 00:08:31,892
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, President Merle.

108
00:08:31,912 --> 00:08:45,032
[SPEAKER_02]: I appreciate you and Vice President Barris putting this forward and I appreciate the Medford Human Rights Commission for their work year-round to advance the cause of human rights and the profile of human rights in Medford and do what we can on the local level.

109
00:08:45,880 --> 00:08:50,281
[SPEAKER_02]: I think my fellow counselors have put this beautifully so far, especially this year.

110
00:08:51,642 --> 00:08:58,044
[SPEAKER_02]: We have constant reminders of how many places across the globe the concept of human rights is just a concept and not a reality.

111
00:08:58,504 --> 00:09:13,389
[SPEAKER_02]: And we also know that for so many people, our neighbors around the world, but also many of our neighbors here in Medford, they can't forget about the potential for the violation of human rights because they're living that every day, or they are under the threat of living their human rights being violated.

112
00:09:13,952 --> 00:09:14,332
[SPEAKER_02]: every day.

113
00:09:15,692 --> 00:09:38,737
[SPEAKER_02]: So we don't have the capacity as a local city council or as a local commission to solve the problem of human rights, but what we can do every day is to hold each other close and to regard every neighbor as sacred and to continue to reaffirm this Medford ordinance, which I really do appreciate for going above and beyond the original one that was commissioned all those years ago.

114
00:09:39,860 --> 00:09:55,764
[SPEAKER_02]: So, with gratitude to the Medford Human Rights Commission for putting this forward, it's always an honor to recommit to this ideal and have the opportunity to think about how to do a better job of implementing this within our community to be a safe haven and a sanctuary for all of our neighbors and all of our future neighbors.

115
00:09:56,064 --> 00:09:56,344
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

116
00:09:57,464 --> 00:09:58,284
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councilor Collins.

117
00:09:58,845 --> 00:10:04,706
[SPEAKER_06]: So, on the motion of vices and bears, as seconded by Councilor Sang, all those in favor?

118
00:10:04,726 --> 00:10:06,146
[SPEAKER_06]: All those opposed?

119
00:10:06,206 --> 00:10:06,906
[SPEAKER_06]: Motion passes.

120
00:10:06,926 --> 00:10:09,207
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Scarpelli?

121
