[SPEAKER_06]: Motion passes.

131
00:10:39,635 --> 00:10:44,317
[SPEAKER_06]: Communications from the Mayor, 23-458, to the Honorable President and members of the Medford City Council.

132
00:10:44,977 --> 00:11:09,424
[SPEAKER_06]: regarding proposed wage adjustment for fire union i respectfully request and recommend the city council approve the following amendments to the revised ordinances chapter 66 article 2 city of medford amendment to revise ordinances chapter 66 article 2 be ordained by the city council of the city of medford in chapter 66 entitled personnel article 2 entitled reserve the city's classification and compensation plan formally included as article 2 section 66 through

133
00:11:11,137 --> 00:11:20,825
[SPEAKER_06]: 6631 through 66-40, amend the figures as they presently appear next to the following title by adjusting each to reflect the following percentage wage increases and effective days.

134
00:11:21,745 --> 00:11:22,045
[SPEAKER_06]: Fire.

135
00:11:22,586 --> 00:11:26,789
[SPEAKER_06]: Effective July 1st, 2021, increase the base salary of all fire union titles by 2.5%.

136
00:11:26,829 --> 00:11:29,491
[SPEAKER_06]: Effective July 1st, 2022, increase the base salary of all fire union titles by 2.5%.

137
00:11:29,531 --> 00:11:32,773
[SPEAKER_06]: Effective July 1st, 2023, increase the base salary of all fire union titles by 3%.

138
00:11:39,422 --> 00:11:43,683
[SPEAKER_06]: Effective July 1st, 2024, increase the base salary of all fire union titles by 3%.

139
00:11:44,264 --> 00:11:48,425
[SPEAKER_06]: Effective July 1st, 2025, increase the base salary of all fire union titles by 2.5%.

140
00:11:49,925 --> 00:11:52,786
[SPEAKER_06]: Human Resources, Lisa Crowley, will be available to answer any questions.

141
00:11:52,986 --> 00:11:54,447
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you for your kind attention to this matter.

142
00:11:54,507 --> 00:11:57,088
[SPEAKER_06]: Respectfully submitted, Bernalongo Kern, Mayor.

143
00:11:58,848 --> 00:12:03,110
[SPEAKER_06]: I know Lisa's back there somewhere too, but Daniel.

144
00:12:04,687 --> 00:12:07,649
[SPEAKER_06]: We obviously have folks from the fire union here as well.

145
00:12:07,889 --> 00:12:13,733
[SPEAKER_06]: If we have any questions from counselors, if we just want to hear from our fire aid reps.

146
00:12:19,212 --> 00:12:20,733
[SPEAKER_08]: would you say to answer any questions?

147
00:12:22,353 --> 00:12:24,874
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know if there's anything you'd like to say here.

148
00:12:25,174 --> 00:12:27,035
[SPEAKER_06]: You're unmuted if you do.

149
00:12:27,515 --> 00:12:39,460
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I just wanted to thank the union for a collaborative process that we went through to get this MOA done and I do appreciate all the work that they put in so that we could come to a collective agreement.

150
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:42,201
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

151
00:12:42,241 --> 00:12:46,022
[SPEAKER_14]: First of all, let me publicly say from

152
00:12:48,977 --> 00:12:55,420
[SPEAKER_14]: this body that we apologize that our firefighters had to wait this long to ratify a contract.

153
00:12:55,500 --> 00:13:00,563
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that it's been a huge disappointment for I think the whole community.

154
00:13:01,303 --> 00:13:06,726
[SPEAKER_14]: And it's something that we hope that will never happen again.

155
00:13:06,746 --> 00:13:10,708
[SPEAKER_14]: To be honest with you, I think

156
00:13:11,903 --> 00:13:18,289
[SPEAKER_14]: It really set the tone for the rest of the community and how people felt about the city of Medford.

157
00:13:18,990 --> 00:13:25,015
[SPEAKER_14]: And when you treat your firefighters the way that you were treated and having to wait this long.

158
00:13:25,716 --> 00:13:34,884
[SPEAKER_14]: I still remember some of the banter back and forth is that the reason why it wasn't negotiated earlier is because you were asking for 9%.

159
00:13:36,897 --> 00:13:38,118
[SPEAKER_14]: Uh, you took 2.5%, 2.5%, 3%, 3%.

160
00:13:39,198 --> 00:13:45,080
[SPEAKER_14]: You didn't, you didn't kill us.

161
00:13:46,101 --> 00:13:47,901
[SPEAKER_14]: And, uh, it's very fair.

162
00:13:48,322 --> 00:13:51,763
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's, I think what you've done is more than fair for our community.

163
00:13:52,443 --> 00:13:54,264
[SPEAKER_14]: So, you know, we thank you for that.

164
00:13:54,384 --> 00:13:56,865
[SPEAKER_14]: I mean, uh, through it all.

165
00:13:57,361 --> 00:13:58,841
[SPEAKER_14]: You still answered every single call.

166
00:13:59,301 --> 00:14:07,183
[SPEAKER_14]: You went into the disease infested homes of the pandemic and did your jobs and, um, above and beyond.

167
00:14:07,283 --> 00:14:22,527
[SPEAKER_14]: So, um, for one person, one counselor, one friend that has supported you guys throughout, uh, my tenure here, um, I'll do that for the rest of my life that, you know, the rest of the time I'm in any power to help our firefighters.

168
00:14:22,587 --> 00:14:24,887
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that, uh, you deserve it and more.

169
00:14:25,248 --> 00:14:27,108
[SPEAKER_14]: Um, you know, it's funny when,

170
00:14:27,493 --> 00:14:37,039
[SPEAKER_14]: You remember the pandemic and they talked about everybody was standing up and supporting our firefighters and police officers and teachers.

171
00:14:37,419 --> 00:14:46,244
[SPEAKER_14]: And it seems like the people that really got kicked in the keister the last couple of years are the people that stood when everybody else couldn't.

172
00:14:46,984 --> 00:14:53,108
[SPEAKER_14]: Um, so I just want to thank you, uh, from the citizens of the city that, uh,

173
00:14:54,681 --> 00:15:01,033
[SPEAKER_14]: enduring this time and finally settling on a contract.

174
00:15:01,053 --> 00:15:01,795
[SPEAKER_14]: I appreciate that.

175
00:15:03,313 --> 00:15:05,935
[SPEAKER_14]: HR director and the hard work that she came in.

176
00:15:05,975 --> 00:15:09,418
[SPEAKER_14]: It's nice to see that we had some change, we see some movement.

177
00:15:09,538 --> 00:15:20,386
[SPEAKER_14]: And one thing that I will hope for, I'll make a recommendation when it comes to the vote that it wants to prove that we waive all the readings and we get you guys paid as fast as we can.

178
00:15:20,446 --> 00:15:25,830
[SPEAKER_14]: And then I know that hopefully I've reached out to the chief of staff.

179
00:15:27,292 --> 00:15:32,335
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't know what's happened the last couple of weeks, but it's been, the city has been getting back to us.

180
00:15:33,292 --> 00:15:34,312
[SPEAKER_14]: in a timely fashion.

181
00:15:34,792 --> 00:15:38,334
[SPEAKER_14]: Any questions I've asked, I've gotten great response from the chief of staff.

182
00:15:38,354 --> 00:15:54,018
[SPEAKER_14]: The question I posed was for the DPW, but I asked also with the firefighters retro, and hopefully they're gonna move that in a timely fashion, not what they've had to go through with the DPW.

183
00:15:54,058 --> 00:16:02,901
[SPEAKER_14]: So I'm hoping that track can follow through for the commitment that you've given us and making sure that you get that money in a timely fashion.

184
00:16:03,561 --> 00:16:04,502
[SPEAKER_14]: your families deserve it.

185
00:16:04,562 --> 00:16:06,763
[SPEAKER_14]: So, again, I'm winded.

186
00:16:06,803 --> 00:16:11,045
[SPEAKER_14]: I could talk about you all night because you deserve it and I just want to thank you.

187
00:16:11,665 --> 00:16:12,726
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

188
00:16:17,008 --> 00:16:17,548
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, councilor.

189
00:16:17,648 --> 00:16:17,948
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

190
00:16:17,968 --> 00:16:25,012
[SPEAKER_01]: I won't go into all the that my fellow council went into but I just want to thank you for the service through all those tough times.

191
00:16:25,032 --> 00:16:27,793
[SPEAKER_01]: You you answer the bell every time people call.

192
00:16:28,353 --> 00:16:28,633
[SPEAKER_01]: I know you

193
00:16:32,709 --> 00:16:33,470
[SPEAKER_01]: Again, just thank you.

194
00:16:33,510 --> 00:16:35,351
[SPEAKER_01]: I want to thank you for having to wait so long.

195
00:16:35,371 --> 00:16:36,772
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm glad you finally settled your contract.

196
00:16:36,792 --> 00:16:37,753
[SPEAKER_01]: So thank you.

197
00:16:38,334 --> 00:16:38,974
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Councilor.

198
00:16:39,414 --> 00:16:40,035
[SPEAKER_06]: Vice Mayor Paris.

199
00:16:40,435 --> 00:16:42,837
[SPEAKER_19]: What are you cooking, Rick?

200
00:16:43,458 --> 00:16:46,880
[SPEAKER_19]: But seriously, I want to echo comments of my fellow Councilors.

201
00:16:47,301 --> 00:16:53,566
[SPEAKER_19]: Glad this is done and that you're going to be getting, you came to an agreement, you're going to be getting these wage increases.

202
00:16:53,606 --> 00:16:53,926
[SPEAKER_19]: And I know

203
00:16:55,754 --> 00:17:04,640
[SPEAKER_19]: If there's anything that we can do to accelerate the process of the retro calculation, Councillor Scarpelli has shared all that information with the council as well about the other units that have been getting work done.

204
00:17:04,700 --> 00:17:05,881
[SPEAKER_19]: So I'd be happy to help.

205
00:17:06,521 --> 00:17:12,145
[SPEAKER_19]: And pending comments from other councillors, I would second Councillor Scarpelli's motion to approve and to waive the readings.

206
00:17:13,438 --> 00:17:14,338
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

207
00:17:14,699 --> 00:17:15,059
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

208
00:17:15,279 --> 00:17:20,041
[SPEAKER_17]: Um, I know it's been incredibly frustrating for you all these last few years.

209
00:17:20,061 --> 00:17:22,462
[SPEAKER_17]: I talked to a lot of voters who are frustrated for you.

210
00:17:22,762 --> 00:17:30,365
[SPEAKER_17]: We'll talk to a lot of family members of firefighters who were particularly frustrated with the process in the last few years.

211
00:17:30,965 --> 00:17:33,526
[SPEAKER_17]: Um, I'm glad that something has finally come.

212
00:17:33,966 --> 00:17:36,107
[SPEAKER_17]: Um, seconding, um,

213
00:17:36,647 --> 00:17:42,753
[SPEAKER_17]: Councilor Scarpell, I mean, seconding all his remarks, but particularly my hope is that this isn't the case.

214
00:17:42,893 --> 00:17:51,080
[SPEAKER_17]: We need to build in more systems of financial accountability on the administration to make sure that we can pay our workers.

215
00:17:52,301 --> 00:17:54,824
[SPEAKER_17]: That's a bigger project that we need to do that

216
00:17:56,423 --> 00:18:05,771
[SPEAKER_17]: will affect all of our frontline staff, especially you guys, but I'm just, I'm really grateful that you all have worked through such frustrating conditions.

217
00:18:06,652 --> 00:18:19,923
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, I, there've been a lot of notable incidents this, in the last calendar year, where the fire department's really stepped in and saved lives that, you know, it was particularly my own neighborhood as well.

218
00:18:20,103 --> 00:18:21,404
[SPEAKER_17]: And so I'm really grateful.

219
00:18:24,857 --> 00:18:25,137
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

220
00:18:25,157 --> 00:18:25,577
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll be brief.

221
00:18:25,597 --> 00:18:30,939
[SPEAKER_02]: My fellow counselors said it already, but thank you for the job that you do all the time, especially during the pandemic.

222
00:18:31,019 --> 00:18:34,620
[SPEAKER_02]: I have probably 1% of the view of just how hard your job is.

223
00:18:34,920 --> 00:18:38,121
[SPEAKER_02]: It's my best friend's father is a retired firefighter and it boggles my mind.

224
00:18:38,161 --> 00:18:39,041
[SPEAKER_02]: I know it's a lifestyle.

225
00:18:39,121 --> 00:18:42,282
[SPEAKER_02]: It stays with you your entire life, your family, their entire life.

226
00:18:42,342 --> 00:18:48,423
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a, it's a lifestyle and a sacrificial one, but thank you for always showing up for the work despite the circumstances.

227
00:18:48,443 --> 00:18:53,945
[SPEAKER_02]: And we'll do what we can on our side to make sure that this long wait doesn't happen again to the extent of our power to do so.

228
00:18:54,265 --> 00:18:54,505
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

229
00:18:55,202 --> 00:18:55,742
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councilor.

230
00:18:56,242 --> 00:18:57,023
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councilor Collins.

231
00:18:57,103 --> 00:19:00,504
[SPEAKER_06]: And like Councilor Collins said, it's all been said, but I'm thankful we're here tonight.

232
00:19:01,024 --> 00:19:04,306
[SPEAKER_06]: A fair contract is the bare minimum we can do for our first responders, for our firefighters.

233
00:19:04,326 --> 00:19:05,426
[SPEAKER_06]: So I'm glad we're finally here.

234
00:19:05,446 --> 00:19:07,467
[SPEAKER_06]: Hopefully this does not happen again.

235
00:19:07,487 --> 00:19:10,828
[SPEAKER_06]: So we have a motion from Councilor Palacio, but I don't know if anyone wants to speak.

236
00:19:11,068 --> 00:19:12,169
[SPEAKER_14]: One more thing, Madam President.

237
00:19:12,649 --> 00:19:13,169
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Palacio.

238
00:19:13,229 --> 00:19:13,509
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

239
00:19:15,556 --> 00:19:16,877
[SPEAKER_14]: Just so you know, this doesn't end here.

240
00:19:16,917 --> 00:19:17,898
[SPEAKER_14]: I think this is the beginning.

241
00:19:18,538 --> 00:19:27,346
[SPEAKER_14]: Um, my first meeting in January, I'm going to push my council members to make sure that we follow through on the, the, uh, fire station and the training tower.

242
00:19:27,826 --> 00:19:31,809
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that's something that is, um, we've waited long enough.

243
00:19:32,309 --> 00:19:34,291
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think the administration has to find a way.

244
00:19:34,351 --> 00:19:42,818
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that I was one of the councils that put forth the debt exclusion that I believed, uh, to, to, to handle those situations, eliminating,

245
00:19:43,410 --> 00:19:59,277
[SPEAKER_14]: the seniors and veterans that our taxes would increase and the debt exclusion, I believe it was $17 a household to make sure that our firefighters have a safe and working environment and a training tower that would support the training of all of our firefighters.

246
00:19:59,317 --> 00:20:01,798
[SPEAKER_14]: So that's something that I will revisit right away.

247
00:20:02,718 --> 00:20:10,222
[SPEAKER_14]: It's not something that we are now, I think that we gotta keep moving forward for what we've done tonight and moving forward.

248
00:20:10,262 --> 00:20:13,003
[SPEAKER_14]: And as a great, not a great man said one time,

249
00:20:14,528 --> 00:20:16,589
[SPEAKER_14]: Mr. Buckley, stand up.

250
00:20:17,609 --> 00:20:18,290
[SPEAKER_14]: You stand up.

251
00:20:18,410 --> 00:20:26,433
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know if you have anything you want to add before we take the motion.

252
00:20:26,933 --> 00:20:27,853
[SPEAKER_11]: Just answering questions.

253
00:20:28,234 --> 00:20:28,654
[SPEAKER_11]: If I may.

254
00:20:29,354 --> 00:20:32,175
[SPEAKER_11]: Thankfully, we do have a contract with the firefighters union.

255
00:20:32,755 --> 00:20:34,536
[SPEAKER_11]: There are other unions in the city that don't.

256
00:20:35,596 --> 00:20:37,337
[SPEAKER_11]: Both police unions do not have one.

257
00:20:37,357 --> 00:20:39,298
[SPEAKER_11]: There's some local 25 unions that don't have one.

258
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:45,689
[SPEAKER_11]: The statewide, I'm sorry, the citywide insurance contract, the PEC contract is still outstanding.

259
00:20:46,229 --> 00:20:47,970
[SPEAKER_11]: It has been since June 30th of 2022.

260
00:20:49,672 --> 00:20:56,177
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'd like to have some more collaborative effort with the personnel director and the city administration to get that on the contract.

261
00:20:56,658 --> 00:21:06,686
[SPEAKER_11]: And I look forward to sitting in the room with the city and the stakeholders, the chief of staff, the mayor, personnel director, and I don't think we need

262
00:21:07,279 --> 00:21:09,760
[SPEAKER_11]: A bunch of lawyers there at $250 an hour.

263
00:21:10,120 --> 00:21:12,900
[SPEAKER_11]: I'd like to handle it in-house with city employees.

264
00:21:13,340 --> 00:21:14,041
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you very much.

265
00:21:14,061 --> 00:21:15,021
[SPEAKER_11]: I appreciate the forum.

266
00:21:15,401 --> 00:21:16,281
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you for all you do.

267
00:21:17,061 --> 00:21:17,381
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

268
00:21:18,081 --> 00:21:26,163
[SPEAKER_06]: So on the motion of Councilor Scarpelli to approve and waive the remainder of the reading, seconded by Vice President Behrs, Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

269
00:21:38,088 --> 00:21:40,950
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, 6 in the affirmative, 0 in the negative, 1 absent.

270
00:21:40,990 --> 00:21:41,751
[SPEAKER_06]: The motion passes.

271
00:21:42,431 --> 00:21:42,691
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

272
00:21:43,051 --> 00:21:45,313
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Madam President.

273
00:21:45,433 --> 00:21:48,315
[SPEAKER_19]: Motion to suspend the rules to take papers 23-461, 23-412, and 23-460.

274
00:21:48,335 --> 00:21:50,676
[SPEAKER_19]: 461 is under suspension.

275
00:21:50,756 --> 00:21:51,677
[SPEAKER_19]: So 461, 412, and 460?

276
00:21:51,777 --> 00:21:51,957
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

277
00:21:51,977 --> 00:21:57,841
[SPEAKER_19]: The rule's already suspended, so motion to take those papers.

278
00:21:57,901 --> 00:21:59,242
[SPEAKER_06]: Are we going to take those papers?

279
00:21:59,262 --> 00:21:59,422
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

280
00:22:06,998 --> 00:22:08,179
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Madam President.

281
00:22:08,199 --> 00:22:11,800
[SPEAKER_06]: I apologize for this not being on the regular agenda.

282
00:22:11,820 --> 00:22:14,882
[SPEAKER_06]: Mr. Maskell's untimely sad passing happened sometime before the agenda was presented.

283
00:22:39,719 --> 00:22:46,120
[SPEAKER_14]: Steve Maskell was a very special person, not only in my life, but I think in many people's lives.

284
00:22:47,481 --> 00:22:52,542
[SPEAKER_14]: He was an outstanding coach, teacher, and then his administrator at Medford High School.

285
00:22:55,042 --> 00:23:07,165
[SPEAKER_14]: For those people that don't know Steve Maskell, he was a kind, funny, strong voice for everybody at Medford High School.

286
00:23:09,308 --> 00:23:17,912
[SPEAKER_14]: I grew up at a time in Medford High School where we only had a few classmates of color, and Mr. Maskell was a strong black man.

287
00:23:18,612 --> 00:23:29,857
[SPEAKER_14]: And for most kids, the first interaction with the man of color, and he was an amazing person.

288
00:23:31,458 --> 00:23:34,039
[SPEAKER_14]: He was someone that really taught you right from wrong.

289
00:23:35,854 --> 00:23:40,795
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm sad to say that I've heard people use language that was off color in front of Mr. Maskell.

290
00:23:42,195 --> 00:23:43,636
[SPEAKER_14]: And I never saw him get angry.

291
00:23:44,456 --> 00:23:46,736
[SPEAKER_14]: I never saw him lose his mind.

292
00:23:47,497 --> 00:23:59,579
[SPEAKER_14]: I've always watched the gentleman who calmly, collectively would bring that young person in and explain what those words meant and how damaging they could be.

293
00:24:02,760 --> 00:24:04,100
[SPEAKER_14]: And he was someone that we all loved.

294
00:24:07,750 --> 00:24:08,831
[SPEAKER_14]: He had such an impact.

295
00:24:09,531 --> 00:24:25,362
[SPEAKER_14]: Personally, for me, I was a very young, immature senior that thought I had the world by the tail and I was going to do anything I wanted until the colleges of my choices, that they just weren't coming.

296
00:24:26,503 --> 00:24:31,286
[SPEAKER_14]: And I remember sitting, crying, 17-year-old kid, just lost.

297
00:24:32,266 --> 00:24:34,348
[SPEAKER_14]: And my parents were immigrants from Italy.

298
00:24:35,044 --> 00:24:35,864
[SPEAKER_14]: They didn't know any better.

299
00:24:36,565 --> 00:24:41,507
[SPEAKER_14]: They went to work every day, three jobs a day, and I was lost.

300
00:24:41,948 --> 00:24:59,877
[SPEAKER_14]: And Mr. Maskell brought me into his office, sat me down, put a plan together, and helped me on my path to become a teacher and a coach and hopefully a positive role model to many students that I've been around.

301
00:25:01,358 --> 00:25:02,699
[SPEAKER_14]: So he changed my life.

302
00:25:03,679 --> 00:25:05,681
[SPEAKER_14]: I talked to his nephew at the Hall of Fame banquet.

303
00:25:05,701 --> 00:25:14,266
[SPEAKER_14]: By the way, he was inducted this past Sunday into the Medford Mustang Hall of Fame, which is a great honor.

304
00:25:14,286 --> 00:25:21,009
[SPEAKER_14]: But he was supposed to be there, and he was taken to the hospital, and his nephew came instead.

305
00:25:22,971 --> 00:25:26,613
[SPEAKER_14]: The stories that went around, what they shared about such a great individual,

306
00:25:27,545 --> 00:25:31,507
[SPEAKER_14]: He's someone that the city is going to greatly miss.

307
00:25:33,508 --> 00:25:34,968
[SPEAKER_14]: He had humor.

308
00:25:35,568 --> 00:25:36,429
[SPEAKER_14]: He had strength.

309
00:25:37,009 --> 00:25:37,829
[SPEAKER_14]: He had knowledge.

310
00:25:38,590 --> 00:25:39,270
[SPEAKER_14]: He had warmth.

311
00:25:40,410 --> 00:25:54,856
[SPEAKER_14]: He was just a good person, somebody that I know my parents are waiting for him at the Pearly Gates, and they're going to sit down and have a big bowl of spaghetti and a glass of wine with him like he did many times at my parents' table.

312
00:25:57,529 --> 00:26:05,392
[SPEAKER_14]: My condolences to the Maskell family, my condolences to the city of Medford, and to all of his former students and athletes.

313
00:26:06,233 --> 00:26:17,598
[SPEAKER_14]: He definitely left a mark that I hope we all can do for the people we come across our lives because he did a remarkable job.

314
00:26:18,298 --> 00:26:20,259
[SPEAKER_14]: So thank you, Steve Maskell.

315
00:26:21,499 --> 00:26:22,380
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Mr. Scarpelli.

316
00:26:24,921 --> 00:26:25,561
[SPEAKER_06]: President Behrs.

317
00:26:25,961 --> 00:26:26,782
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you, Madam President.

318
00:26:28,397 --> 00:26:39,221
[SPEAKER_19]: I didn't have the same relationship that Councilor Scarpelli did, but my first year at Medford High School was Mr. Mask's last year at Medford High School, and he was the senior class submaster assistant principal.

319
00:26:39,241 --> 00:26:40,581
[SPEAKER_19]: They changed the title to later.

320
00:26:42,582 --> 00:26:55,066
[SPEAKER_19]: When I was there, and all I really knew of him was that he was both the person who didn't want to do something wrong in front of in the hall, but also the person who wasn't going to yell at you

321
00:26:56,179 --> 00:27:09,961
[SPEAKER_19]: If you did it right and I think that that speaks more to George's example it wasn't it wasn't you know there's people who who walk the halls and and enforce order through screaming and shouting and he enforced order through a stern look and then you just walk to the office.

322
00:27:11,863 --> 00:27:33,860
[SPEAKER_19]: But beyond that, you know, it was clear to me that he was a mentor to a lot of folks, that he had a long history in the building, that he meant a lot, not just to the students in that grade, but people who came before, to educators in the building, to the community and the links with the community through sports and through other activities, but also through

323
00:27:34,631 --> 00:27:54,917
[SPEAKER_19]: how many kids he wrote a recommendation for to go to college, and how many folks he helped who were struggling, who didn't maybe have the knowledge or the resources or time at home from their parents to help them navigate the difficulties that come when you go from high school into college or into work or into the trades or anything else.

324
00:27:56,518 --> 00:28:01,560
[SPEAKER_19]: I remember also how everyone felt when they found out that he was leaving at the end of the year.

325
00:28:03,201 --> 00:28:13,465
[SPEAKER_19]: And the fact that it was like, you know, and I'm like 14, I don't really know much, but it was clear to me that there were people who knew that that presence no longer being there was going to be really significant.

326
00:28:13,945 --> 00:28:20,487
[SPEAKER_19]: And I didn't quite get how much of that was true until right now, when I heard what George said.

327
00:28:22,745 --> 00:28:30,967
[SPEAKER_19]: sorry, to you, to his family, and to everybody that he was so meaningful to in our community and beyond.

328
00:28:31,408 --> 00:28:31,748
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

329
00:28:32,148 --> 00:28:32,448
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

330
00:28:33,768 --> 00:28:37,549
[SPEAKER_06]: On the motion of Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by Councilor Carviello, all those in favor?

331
00:28:38,290 --> 00:28:38,950
[SPEAKER_06]: All those opposed?

332
00:28:39,110 --> 00:28:41,591
[SPEAKER_06]: Dedicate?

333
00:28:41,971 --> 00:28:42,351
[SPEAKER_06]: Absolutely.

334
00:28:43,091 --> 00:28:46,152
[SPEAKER_06]: On the motion of Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by Councilor Carviello, all those in favor?

335
00:28:46,172 --> 00:28:47,672
[SPEAKER_06]: All those opposed?

336
00:28:47,692 --> 00:28:48,333
[SPEAKER_06]: The motion passes.

337
00:28:48,373 --> 00:28:49,593
[SPEAKER_06]: Please rise for a moment of silence.

338
00:28:55,325 --> 00:28:55,427
you

339
00:29:08,264 --> 00:29:12,886
[SPEAKER_06]: 23-412, Adam Dash and Associates, Attorneys at Law.

340
00:29:13,326 --> 00:29:16,447
[SPEAKER_06]: I've read this a few times, so I'm just gonna skip this.

341
00:29:17,407 --> 00:29:18,007
[SPEAKER_06]: Attention, Adam.

342
00:29:18,067 --> 00:29:18,788
[SPEAKER_06]: Heard of me, City Clerk.

343
