425
00:34:48,893 --> 00:34:52,014
[SPEAKER_06]: 23446, legal notice of a public hearing, City of Medford.

426
00:34:52,174 --> 00:35:00,817
[SPEAKER_06]: The Medford City Council will hold a public hearing in the Howard F. Alden Chambers at Medford City Hall, 85 George P. Hadsett Drive, Medford, Mass., and via Zoom on Tuesday, November 28th, 2023 at 7 p.m.

427
00:35:03,354 --> 00:35:07,635
[SPEAKER_06]: A link to this hearing will be posted no later than Friday, November 24th, 2023.

428
00:35:08,156 --> 00:35:16,819
[SPEAKER_06]: The purpose of the hearing is to hear the Board of Assessors on the following items for the purpose of allocation of the FY 2024 property tax.

429
00:35:17,179 --> 00:35:19,840
[SPEAKER_06]: One, to determine the residential factor to be used for FY 2024.

430
00:35:19,880 --> 00:35:22,741
[SPEAKER_06]: Two, select an open space discount.

431
00:35:22,861 --> 00:35:24,581
[SPEAKER_06]: Three, select a residential exemption.

432
00:35:24,701 --> 00:35:26,482
[SPEAKER_06]: Four, select a small commercial exemption.

433
00:35:27,122 --> 00:35:28,282
[SPEAKER_06]: Call 781-393-2501 for any aides accommodations.

434
00:35:28,302 --> 00:35:28,463
[SPEAKER_06]: TDD 781-393-2501.

435
00:35:34,006 --> 00:35:36,988
[SPEAKER_06]: 2516, the city of Medford is an EEOAA 504 employer.

436
00:35:37,068 --> 00:35:45,573
[SPEAKER_06]: For additional information, contact the office of the city clerk at 71-393-2425 by order of the Medford City Council, signed Adam L. Herdimese, the city clerk.

437
00:35:45,773 --> 00:35:52,137
[SPEAKER_06]: And we have Chief Assessor Costigan here with us tonight, who already has a presentation about to get started on the screen.

438
00:35:52,638 --> 00:35:56,620
[SPEAKER_06]: Unless the councilors have any questions to start, we can go right to the presentation.

439
00:35:58,498 --> 00:35:58,938
[SPEAKER_12]: Good evening.

440
00:35:58,958 --> 00:36:00,339
[SPEAKER_12]: It's a pleasure to be here.

441
00:36:01,540 --> 00:36:14,648
[SPEAKER_12]: The assessing office works hard every year to develop fair cash values for our over 18,000 parcels, and this tax policy is left to the council to decide, so I'm going to just take you through a few policy options we have.

442
00:36:15,028 --> 00:36:20,251
[SPEAKER_12]: Tonight we'll be adopting the city's tax policy by allocating the class among the property types.

443
00:36:22,368 --> 00:36:24,669
[SPEAKER_12]: And these are the three votes we'll make.

444
00:36:25,789 --> 00:36:40,173
[SPEAKER_12]: Either a single tax rate or maintain the 175% shift of the tax levy from the residential class to the commercial, industrial, personal property class, voting on whether to adopt a residential exemption and whether to adopt a small commercial exemption.

445
00:36:42,278 --> 00:36:54,164
[SPEAKER_12]: So just to review our property evaluation process, we take calendar year 2022 sales and they're used to establish our fiscal year 24 values.

446
00:36:54,844 --> 00:37:01,208
[SPEAKER_12]: By state law, we're between 90 and 110% on an assessment to sales ratio and each class.

447
00:37:01,768 --> 00:37:04,269
[SPEAKER_12]: We submitted all our values to the Department of Revenue.

448
00:37:04,809 --> 00:37:07,691
[SPEAKER_12]: They approved our values that I'm presenting tonight on November 6th.

449
00:37:10,316 --> 00:37:23,768
[SPEAKER_12]: As you can see, it's hard to see on the screen, but each of our classes, single family, condo, two family, three family apartment, commercial, industrial, have to be within the 90 to 110% ratio.

450
00:37:24,188 --> 00:37:28,432
[SPEAKER_12]: For instance, our single families this year had an assessment to sales ratio of 0.92.

451
00:37:32,042 --> 00:37:40,868
[SPEAKER_12]: This just gives you an idea of our fiscal year 23 average assessment versus our 24 average assessment and the percentage change.

452
00:37:42,008 --> 00:37:49,213
[SPEAKER_12]: Again, values are multiplied by the tax rate and that is how the tax bill is derived for each property owner in Bedford.

453
00:37:52,173 --> 00:38:03,019
[SPEAKER_12]: This slide just depicts the average single family condo, two family, three family apartment commercial industrial property in regards to our surrounding communities.

454
00:38:07,061 --> 00:38:10,363
[SPEAKER_12]: And the percent change in each of those classes.

455
00:38:11,043 --> 00:38:16,646
[SPEAKER_12]: So we saw about a 7% increase, valuation increase in our single families this year.

456
00:38:19,205 --> 00:38:21,086
[SPEAKER_12]: New growth, I wanna touch on quickly.

457
00:38:21,106 --> 00:38:26,589
[SPEAKER_12]: The Department of Revenue did approve on November 6th our new growth number.

458
00:38:27,410 --> 00:38:29,371
[SPEAKER_12]: I wanna point out Jim O'Brien's here.

459
00:38:29,411 --> 00:38:30,992
[SPEAKER_12]: He's our part-time field assessor.

460
00:38:31,272 --> 00:38:31,912
[SPEAKER_12]: He's back here.

461
00:38:32,393 --> 00:38:38,276
[SPEAKER_12]: He has been instrumental in our property visitation process and our capture of new growth.

462
00:38:38,936 --> 00:38:42,358
[SPEAKER_12]: We captured 2.85 million in new growth.

463
00:38:42,438 --> 00:38:44,299
[SPEAKER_12]: And as a reminder, other than the Prop 2 1⁄2,

464
00:38:45,925 --> 00:38:51,408
[SPEAKER_12]: and I guess a debt exclusion if you chose to do that, this is the only way to increase the tax levy.

465
00:38:52,308 --> 00:39:02,573
[SPEAKER_12]: So as you might know, 72% of our city revenues come from this tax levy, so this is kind of the only way to sort of capture more growth in that area and increase revenues for the city.

466
00:39:04,234 --> 00:39:12,898
[SPEAKER_12]: We had, again, 2.8 million, and I know this is hard to see, but about half and half between commercial and residential.

467
00:39:15,757 --> 00:39:17,879
[SPEAKER_12]: Again, this was our best year for new growth.

468
00:39:18,519 --> 00:39:23,023
[SPEAKER_12]: I do thank our staff, including Jim, our field assessor, and Jared, our assistant assessor.

469
00:39:23,624 --> 00:39:33,292
[SPEAKER_12]: We had a 30% increase in new growth this year, and that is what a fully staffed office can do going forward, and we appreciate that come budget time.

470
00:39:36,635 --> 00:39:40,958
[SPEAKER_12]: And the fiscal year 24 value by class, I just wanna touch on.

471
00:39:41,138 --> 00:39:43,901
[SPEAKER_12]: So 89% of our value is from the residential class.

472
00:39:45,273 --> 00:39:51,123
[SPEAKER_12]: 8% from commercial one and a quarter from industrial and 1.76 from the personal property class

473
00:39:52,898 --> 00:39:56,019
[SPEAKER_12]: So the first thing we're asking today is that shift.

474
00:39:56,119 --> 00:40:04,683
[SPEAKER_12]: If we did not shift the levy, it would be $9.39 tax rate applied to all of these values across the board.

475
00:40:05,283 --> 00:40:20,190
[SPEAKER_12]: What the City of Bedford has done in the past, it has shifted these values to the commercial industrial personal property class, and that creates a split rate where the residential gets brought down to $8.52, and the commercial industrial personal property gets brought up to 16.43.

476
00:40:22,542 --> 00:40:24,124
[SPEAKER_12]: This shows the percent.

477
00:40:24,165 --> 00:40:26,027
[SPEAKER_12]: So as you saw, it was about 89% of the value.

478
00:40:26,047 --> 00:40:28,932
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, it brings it down to about 80% of the levy.

479
00:40:31,375 --> 00:40:36,443
[SPEAKER_12]: And the selection of the minimum residential factor is the way we drive this to get to that 175% split.

480
00:40:39,015 --> 00:41:00,385
[SPEAKER_12]: And what that does, as you can see, at the one, if we didn't do the split, you can see the residential commercial breakdown, and at the 175% split, it again brings that tax rate on the residential down from 939 to 852, and brings the CIP, commercial industrial personal property, up to 1643 from the 939.

481
00:41:01,346 --> 00:41:08,269
[SPEAKER_12]: These might be rounded by a penny during our tax recap, but these are estimates and good estimates.

482
00:41:09,762 --> 00:41:21,366
[SPEAKER_12]: Just to give the impact on a single family home, were we not to do this, single tax rate, the 939, the average single family house would have about a $7,200 bill.

483
00:41:21,426 --> 00:41:31,049
[SPEAKER_12]: The effect of this policy has been implemented in the previous years by city council, draws that tax bill for that average single family down to 6,551.

484
00:41:31,109 --> 00:41:32,349
[SPEAKER_12]: That's the savings.

485
00:41:38,432 --> 00:41:48,976
[SPEAKER_12]: This is a historical chart, the average single family going from 718 to 768,000, fiscal year 23 to 24.

486
00:41:49,596 --> 00:41:52,797
[SPEAKER_12]: The year over year change in tax dollars, about $336.

487
00:41:52,837 --> 00:41:55,658
[SPEAKER_14]: Point of information, Madam President.

488
00:41:56,398 --> 00:42:00,860
[SPEAKER_14]: Just to, I know we're gonna get questions.

489
00:42:01,180 --> 00:42:01,440
[SPEAKER_10]: Yep.

490
00:42:01,700 --> 00:42:06,442
[SPEAKER_14]: The slide that went up said that our assessed values have gone up by 7%.

491
00:42:08,357 --> 00:42:10,799
[SPEAKER_14]: We're going to have phone calls saying taxes are going to be raised by 7%.

492
00:42:11,359 --> 00:42:15,302
[SPEAKER_12]: That's incorrect because the tax rate's going down.

493
00:42:15,782 --> 00:42:15,922
[SPEAKER_14]: Right.

494
00:42:15,942 --> 00:42:16,723
[SPEAKER_14]: So, okay.

495
00:42:17,243 --> 00:42:21,866
[SPEAKER_14]: But when they read the tax bill, this is what, so the understanding, because we're going to get phone calls.

496
00:42:24,087 --> 00:42:29,031
[SPEAKER_14]: So the taxes, our taxes are going to go down, but the assessment's going up.

497
00:42:29,411 --> 00:42:32,593
[SPEAKER_14]: So the tax bill now will read higher.

498
00:42:33,863 --> 00:42:38,524
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes, the average single family tax bill, on average, would be about $336 higher.

499
00:42:38,884 --> 00:42:46,266
[SPEAKER_14]: OK, so again, just people, when I start getting the phone calls in 15 minutes, it's not saying, George, our taxes are going to go up.

500
00:42:46,866 --> 00:42:49,347
[SPEAKER_14]: This city, we don't street sweep.

501
00:42:49,367 --> 00:42:50,307
[SPEAKER_14]: We don't fix the trees.

502
00:42:50,347 --> 00:42:51,147
[SPEAKER_14]: The parks are a mess.

503
00:42:51,787 --> 00:42:58,549
[SPEAKER_14]: So the understanding is that our assessment has risen, not the tax rate.

504
00:42:59,509 --> 00:42:59,829
[SPEAKER_12]: Correct.

505
00:42:59,869 --> 00:43:01,089
[SPEAKER_12]: The values have gone up 7%.

506
00:43:01,630 --> 00:43:02,950
[SPEAKER_12]: The tax rate has dropped.

507
00:43:03,862 --> 00:43:10,308
[SPEAKER_19]: And just to further clarify, just the tax, the year over year change in bill is less than the increase in the valuation.

508
00:43:12,430 --> 00:43:13,551
[SPEAKER_19]: Values are increasing fast.

509
00:43:13,591 --> 00:43:13,991
[SPEAKER_12]: Correct.

510
00:43:14,131 --> 00:43:14,371
[SPEAKER_12]: Correct.

511
00:43:14,392 --> 00:43:15,052
[SPEAKER_12]: That's a good way to put it.

512
00:43:15,072 --> 00:43:15,292
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes.

513
00:43:15,312 --> 00:43:17,174
[SPEAKER_14]: Now the values general everywhere.

514
00:43:17,734 --> 00:43:23,640
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think that people, you know, have to understand that because I know I'm going to get, I'm going to get the phone calls saying that what's wrong with you.

515
00:43:24,220 --> 00:43:26,022
[SPEAKER_14]: I voted for you and you're raising my taxes.

516
00:43:26,607 --> 00:43:28,309
[SPEAKER_14]: So I just want to make sure it's clear.

517
00:43:28,690 --> 00:43:32,634
[SPEAKER_14]: So they, they, that I set the dialogue for these future phone calls.

518
00:43:33,275 --> 00:43:33,836
[SPEAKER_14]: Absolutely.

519
00:43:33,916 --> 00:43:35,077
[SPEAKER_14]: So thank you.

520
00:43:37,394 --> 00:43:42,959
[SPEAKER_12]: Yep, so the other two parts, two votes we're making tonight, residential exemption.

521
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:50,185
[SPEAKER_12]: This option is generally established early in the fiscal year so that it gives the assessing office time to implement it.

522
00:43:50,946 --> 00:43:58,812
[SPEAKER_12]: The residential exemption in Medford, if we did adopt it at that 35% exemption, the break-even would be approximately $936,000.

523
00:43:58,892 --> 00:43:59,233
[SPEAKER_12]: So any

524
00:44:02,075 --> 00:44:08,840
[SPEAKER_12]: property on the residential properties valued over $936,000 would experience a tax increase.

525
00:44:09,220 --> 00:44:12,142
[SPEAKER_12]: Those below it would experience a tax decrease.

526
00:44:12,623 --> 00:44:18,787
[SPEAKER_12]: There are about 18 communities in the state that have implemented a residential exemption.

527
00:44:20,515 --> 00:44:23,017
[SPEAKER_12]: And the same with granting a small commercial exemption.

528
00:44:23,078 --> 00:44:27,101
[SPEAKER_12]: Generally, early in the spring, we would do this proceeding that started the fiscal year.

529
00:44:28,683 --> 00:44:41,855
[SPEAKER_12]: There is a provision in Mass General Law to give businesses a 10% exemption on values of less than a million dollars that employ 10 people or more.

530
00:44:44,029 --> 00:44:55,012
[SPEAKER_12]: So just to clarify the vote summary, we'll be voting tonight on that minimum residential factor as we have in previous years, the residential exemption and the small commercial exemption.

531
00:44:55,933 --> 00:44:57,793
[SPEAKER_12]: And I'll take any questions at this time.

532
00:45:00,844 --> 00:45:01,964
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you, Madam President.

533
00:45:01,984 --> 00:45:13,687
[SPEAKER_19]: I think similar to Councillor Scarbelli, you know, the way that Proposition 2.5 works makes it very hard for the average person to understand how taxes are affected.

534
00:45:13,707 --> 00:45:18,568
[SPEAKER_19]: Proposition 2.5 doesn't mean everyone's individual bill only goes up 2.5% per year.

535
00:45:18,668 --> 00:45:19,728
[SPEAKER_19]: It doesn't mean that at all.

536
00:45:20,368 --> 00:45:23,369
[SPEAKER_19]: It means the levy goes up 2.5% in the aggregate.

537
00:45:24,109 --> 00:45:28,430
[SPEAKER_19]: And how that's distributed is based on assessed value times the tax rate.

538
00:45:31,077 --> 00:45:34,180
[SPEAKER_19]: One thing I like to highlight is that the tax rate in Medford is less than 1%.

539
00:45:35,201 --> 00:45:35,421
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes.

540
00:45:35,441 --> 00:45:40,586
[SPEAKER_19]: 0.852 if we do the full shift, I think is what you said, or maybe off by a digit there.

541
00:45:40,786 --> 00:45:41,286
[SPEAKER_12]: That's correct.

542
00:45:41,387 --> 00:45:45,851
[SPEAKER_19]: So probably the lowest tax rate you'll find on a tax anywhere.

543
00:45:47,652 --> 00:45:50,715
[SPEAKER_19]: My main questions are around a few things.

544
00:45:50,995 --> 00:45:53,558
[SPEAKER_19]: One, new growth seems really strong at 2.8 million.

545
00:45:55,897 --> 00:45:59,664
[SPEAKER_19]: And one thing I noticed was there was a pretty big increase in the personal property valuation.

546
00:45:59,684 --> 00:46:05,333
[SPEAKER_19]: Do you have any further kind of information on either of those questions that you can share, like how we captured so much?

547
00:46:05,394 --> 00:46:08,940
[SPEAKER_19]: It sounds like you credited some to full staffing levels in the department.

548
00:46:09,298 --> 00:46:09,718
[SPEAKER_12]: Absolutely.

549
00:46:10,559 --> 00:46:14,622
[SPEAKER_12]: Anytime, so first of all, yes, the staffing levels in the department are crucial.

550
00:46:15,162 --> 00:46:21,267
[SPEAKER_12]: We cannot capture the growth if we're not going out and seeing the growth, if we're not pulling up all the permits to align with the growth.

551
00:46:21,527 --> 00:46:26,571
[SPEAKER_12]: Whenever we submit growth to this state for approval, it's gonna mention that permit.

552
00:46:26,971 --> 00:46:28,292
[SPEAKER_12]: And so we have to do the work.

553
00:46:28,593 --> 00:46:30,534
[SPEAKER_12]: We had over 1,000 entries in new growth this year.

554
00:46:30,834 --> 00:46:32,295
[SPEAKER_12]: That was up 30% right there.

555
00:46:32,996 --> 00:46:36,419
[SPEAKER_12]: In addition, this year, we had large permits in the industrial space.

556
00:46:37,159 --> 00:46:41,761
[SPEAKER_12]: We also had several exempt to taxable parcels.

557
00:46:42,261 --> 00:46:43,102
[SPEAKER_12]: One was across the street.

558
00:46:43,622 --> 00:46:44,422
[SPEAKER_12]: That's all new growth.

559
00:46:45,243 --> 00:46:48,524
[SPEAKER_12]: It's on the medical center across the street.

560
00:46:48,544 --> 00:46:54,207
[SPEAKER_12]: And lastly, there was a personal property audit that resulted in hiring new growth there as well.

561
00:46:55,203 --> 00:46:58,645
[SPEAKER_19]: Great, and that's a good transition to kind of my next question.

562
00:46:59,086 --> 00:47:12,834
[SPEAKER_19]: You hear a lot of rumblings and rumblings online of things aren't assessed fairly, people get favorable assessments because of who they know, and this person's paying very low taxes, and my assessment always seems to go up a ton.

563
00:47:13,495 --> 00:47:22,521
[SPEAKER_19]: Could you explain a little bit more about the assessment process and how, both in your office and because of the state review, it's legally and procedurally impossible for that to be happening in the city?

564
00:47:23,258 --> 00:47:23,939
[SPEAKER_12]: Sure, absolutely.

565
00:47:25,041 --> 00:47:33,894
[SPEAKER_12]: So every year our office is responsible with basically deriving the fair cash value of each parcel.

566
00:47:35,230 --> 00:47:37,691
[SPEAKER_12]: the previous 1st of January.

567
00:47:37,791 --> 00:47:42,313
[SPEAKER_12]: So for fiscal year 24, it's gonna be 1-1-23, the 1st of January 23.

568
00:47:43,033 --> 00:47:47,175
[SPEAKER_12]: We take great pride in doing property reviews and inspections.

569
00:47:47,255 --> 00:47:50,396
[SPEAKER_12]: So any, I call it property record card change.

570
00:47:50,416 --> 00:48:01,800
[SPEAKER_12]: If you add a kitchen, if you add a bath, if you're putting an addition on, if you're adding to your parcel, we have the field staff now to capture that and update the property record cards.

571
00:48:03,501 --> 00:48:05,903
[SPEAKER_12]: a process that takes several months.

572
00:48:06,103 --> 00:48:12,887
[SPEAKER_12]: We are also engaging in a cyclical project where every 10 years we are going to the property and doing a physical inspection.

573
00:48:13,508 --> 00:48:16,149
[SPEAKER_12]: You may see a number of your constituents now get letters.

574
00:48:16,650 --> 00:48:20,312
[SPEAKER_12]: We always now send letters before we do any of that.

575
00:48:20,932 --> 00:48:29,098
[SPEAKER_12]: Once I have all the data together, we can then make market adjustments, and we do that in the commercial space, the industrial space, and the residential space.

576
00:48:30,033 --> 00:48:36,736
[SPEAKER_12]: Those market adjustments are based on the sales sampling, really, in the calendar year preceding the fiscal year.

577
00:48:37,056 --> 00:48:40,578
[SPEAKER_12]: We're using those sales to inform our market adjustments.

578
00:48:41,458 --> 00:48:45,080
[SPEAKER_12]: So there's really no window whereby we could be preferential.

579
00:48:46,593 --> 00:48:48,234
[SPEAKER_12]: It doesn't really exist in our office.

580
00:48:49,975 --> 00:48:53,838
[SPEAKER_12]: We are happy to talk through valuations with taxpayers.

581
00:48:54,138 --> 00:48:58,901
[SPEAKER_12]: In fact, if they call in and they want to do a physical inspection, we'll make it happen that week.

582
00:48:59,502 --> 00:49:01,063
[SPEAKER_12]: We'll be right on the ball in that regard.

583
00:49:01,643 --> 00:49:04,145
[SPEAKER_12]: But that's really the process.

584
00:49:05,426 --> 00:49:10,629
[SPEAKER_19]: So if a resident says, hey, I think the valuations are way out of whack, they could call your office and they could talk through it?

585
00:49:10,969 --> 00:49:14,512
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, and on January 1st through February 1st, they can file an abatement.

586
00:49:14,592 --> 00:49:15,452
[SPEAKER_19]: They can even file an abatement.

587
00:49:15,532 --> 00:49:15,913
[SPEAKER_12]: Exactly.

588
00:49:16,622 --> 00:49:25,490
[SPEAKER_19]: Okay, I just think that's important to know because I think there's just false rumors constantly spread online that assess values are politically motivated.

589
00:49:25,530 --> 00:49:30,735
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think that that is the, it undermines, you know, you guys and the hard work that you do.

590
00:49:31,316 --> 00:49:33,338
[SPEAKER_19]: And just so I understand it, the valuation,

591
00:49:33,918 --> 00:49:36,700
[SPEAKER_19]: The state also does some sort of certification of the valuation?

592
00:49:36,760 --> 00:49:36,920
[SPEAKER_12]: Yep.

593
00:49:37,180 --> 00:49:40,603
[SPEAKER_12]: So we had to submit to the state and they approve the values every year.

594
00:49:40,623 --> 00:49:45,326
[SPEAKER_19]: So it's not just a process of integrity in your office, but also there's the oversight of the state.

595
00:49:45,766 --> 00:49:46,147
[SPEAKER_19]: Exactly.

596
00:49:46,487 --> 00:49:46,707
[SPEAKER_19]: Great.

597
00:49:48,248 --> 00:49:48,969
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you for that.

598
00:49:51,150 --> 00:49:52,931
[SPEAKER_19]: Just two more questions.

599
00:49:56,980 --> 00:50:00,281
[SPEAKER_19]: What we just did to extend the valuation year, when does that hit?

600
00:50:00,301 --> 00:50:02,641
[SPEAKER_19]: Does that hit us next time we calculate?

601
00:50:02,661 --> 00:50:04,282
[SPEAKER_12]: That'll be fiscal year 25, yes.

602
00:50:04,342 --> 00:50:08,303
[SPEAKER_12]: We'll be able to pick up new growth through June 30th as opposed to January 1st.

603
00:50:08,523 --> 00:50:09,483
[SPEAKER_19]: Great, thank you.

604
00:50:10,183 --> 00:50:15,004
[SPEAKER_19]: And then I think the big policy question that we look at every time we have the classification hearing is the residential exemption.

605
00:50:15,024 --> 00:50:22,106
[SPEAKER_19]: To me, I think there's a lot of reasons why we could move in that direction, and I think it could be a very good thing.

606
00:50:22,146 --> 00:50:24,867
[SPEAKER_19]: I think it could especially be a way to help mitigate

607
00:50:26,062 --> 00:50:34,087
[SPEAKER_19]: fact that we have massive need and we're likely to explore the override and debt exclusion tool for a number of massive projects over the next several years.

608
00:50:36,348 --> 00:50:40,311
[SPEAKER_19]: There's big projects we have to do and we have understaffing.

609
00:50:40,351 --> 00:50:46,795
[SPEAKER_19]: As you're aware, your staff levels finally hit where you need to be and suddenly you're able to do things that your office hasn't been able to do for a very long time.

610
00:50:47,435 --> 00:50:51,877
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'm glad we prioritized that, but I think if I talked to any department head in the building, they would say the same thing.

611
00:50:52,137 --> 00:50:55,859
[SPEAKER_19]: Our level of service would be much better if we had the staff levels that we need.

612
00:50:56,799 --> 00:51:09,966
[SPEAKER_19]: So just given that fact, I personally think, and as you said, the tax policy sits with us, I think the resident exemption could be a way to mitigate for certain people, for owner occupied under the break even, the impact of an overrider or debt exclusion.

613
00:51:09,986 --> 00:51:12,747
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think we need to explore that.

614
00:51:13,167 --> 00:51:14,568
[SPEAKER_19]: But my two questions here are one,

615
00:51:15,017 --> 00:51:20,019
[SPEAKER_19]: This break even seems significantly higher than the last time we looked at this last year.

616
00:51:20,039 --> 00:51:27,061
[SPEAKER_19]: Are we expecting that the break even is going to go up over time or down over time, or is that not something that we can kind of project?

617
00:51:27,562 --> 00:51:29,822
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, as values go up, it's going to go up over time.

618
00:51:29,842 --> 00:51:30,363
[SPEAKER_12]: That's correct.

619
00:51:30,483 --> 00:51:30,663
[SPEAKER_19]: Yep.

620
00:51:31,103 --> 00:51:31,383
[SPEAKER_19]: All right.

621
00:51:31,683 --> 00:51:36,805
[SPEAKER_19]: Um, and, and what that means just so that folks can have a little more understanding of it too, right?

622
00:51:37,405 --> 00:51:42,127
[SPEAKER_19]: Basically like the lower your houses, your, your home, your residential property is valued.

623
00:51:43,411 --> 00:51:50,974
[SPEAKER_19]: the more the exemption matters, and then the closer you get to that 936 figure, essentially the exemption matters less.

624
00:51:51,054 --> 00:51:57,996
[SPEAKER_19]: Once you hit that figure, the exemption is not matching up with the increased tax that you're paying because the rate went up.

625
00:51:58,076 --> 00:51:59,016
[SPEAKER_12]: The rate went up, exactly.

626
00:51:59,356 --> 00:52:00,717
[SPEAKER_12]: Yep, that's exactly correct.

627
00:52:01,377 --> 00:52:09,019
[SPEAKER_19]: And so just for your office, and we asked your predecessor this several times, and I'm guessing the answer's gonna be similar, and you kind of included it in your presentation.

628
00:52:09,839 --> 00:52:11,360
[SPEAKER_19]: If we wanted to go in that direction,

629
00:52:12,732 --> 00:52:17,001
[SPEAKER_19]: what timing would you need to implement an exemption?

630
00:52:18,052 --> 00:52:26,196
[SPEAKER_12]: It would be timing before the start of the fiscal year because in communities that do allow the residence exemption, they have applications start July 1st.

631
00:52:27,057 --> 00:52:32,359
[SPEAKER_12]: And that's just helpful because in year one, I would expect us to get around 10,000 applications.

632
00:52:32,900 --> 00:52:36,782
[SPEAKER_12]: Each application has to be reviewed because we have to certify that they are a resident of Medford.

633
00:52:37,162 --> 00:52:42,645
[SPEAKER_12]: We would ask for the redacted page one of their Massachusetts state income tax return listing the Medford address.

634
00:52:43,465 --> 00:52:48,510
[SPEAKER_12]: That would be an extremely time-consuming process, in year one particularly.

635
00:52:48,830 --> 00:52:55,556
[SPEAKER_12]: And so I would be asking the mayor and council for an additional staff member to accomplish that task.

636
00:52:57,277 --> 00:52:58,539
[SPEAKER_12]: That would be the administrative cost.

637
00:52:59,159 --> 00:53:07,246
[SPEAKER_12]: To your point about it really shifts the tax around within the residential class.

638
00:53:08,408 --> 00:53:14,804
[SPEAKER_12]: It also pushes up significantly the tax borne by apartments.

639
00:53:17,113 --> 00:53:36,293
[SPEAKER_12]: being cognizant of that, I mention that because basic economics, if a landlord is going to experience a significant increase in their taxes, they're going to push that on to the rental class, the tenants, who if that's the policy outcome, that's something that council should be aware of.

640
00:53:38,075 --> 00:53:48,747
[SPEAKER_12]: But yes, to your point, condominiums would see a reduction, single families a reduction, two families depending on the value, three families and apartments, the tax burden would go up on those classes.

641
00:53:49,268 --> 00:53:56,056
[SPEAKER_19]: And it would be progressively metered because basically the same way that your exemption loses value to the breakeven.

642
00:53:56,676 --> 00:53:59,717
[SPEAKER_19]: The increase above the break-even is also, yeah.

643
00:54:00,478 --> 00:54:00,998
[SPEAKER_12]: Exactly.

644
00:54:01,698 --> 00:54:04,600
[SPEAKER_12]: So a large apartment building would have a large tax increase.

645
00:54:04,680 --> 00:54:10,462
[SPEAKER_19]: A 500-unit building is going to see a very large increase versus a three-family is going to be maybe not so bad.

646
00:54:13,166 --> 00:54:22,635
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'll leave the basic economics to another day, because my opinion is that the rents are set by the market, and you only have an indirect impact of a tax increase on rental price.

647
00:54:23,236 --> 00:54:25,378
[SPEAKER_19]: But you can go either way on that.

648
00:54:25,538 --> 00:54:35,808
[SPEAKER_19]: But essentially, you would need, for us to have made this decision six months ago, in order for it to be... If we were to vote on it tonight, you would have needed six months of implementation time.

649
00:54:37,543 --> 00:54:38,765
[SPEAKER_12]: Especially year one, yeah.

650
00:54:39,065 --> 00:54:40,787
[SPEAKER_12]: It would be a deluge of papers.

651
00:54:41,488 --> 00:54:42,289
[SPEAKER_19]: Got it.

652
00:54:42,770 --> 00:54:43,691
[SPEAKER_19]: Much appreciated.

653
00:54:43,911 --> 00:54:50,740
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think we just need to keep that in mind, that if we're going to make this decision, we're probably not making it tonight at the classification hearing.

654
00:54:51,100 --> 00:54:51,440
[SPEAKER_12]: Correct.

655
00:54:52,442 --> 00:54:52,662
[SPEAKER_19]: Great.

656
00:54:53,263 --> 00:54:53,884
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you so much.

657
00:54:56,521 --> 00:54:57,301
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you to that point.

658
00:54:57,341 --> 00:55:08,566
[SPEAKER_14]: I know that your predecessor really stressed the negative impact on the owner-occupied because of the fact that it might hurt more than it helps.

659
00:55:09,327 --> 00:55:15,709
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think that that resonates for, especially with, you know, when you're talking about keeping families in Medford.

660
00:55:17,521 --> 00:55:19,682
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, I lived in a two-family.

661
00:55:19,762 --> 00:55:20,922
[SPEAKER_14]: We owned a two-family.

662
00:55:22,002 --> 00:55:24,423
[SPEAKER_14]: I lived in a neighborhood of two, three-family houses.

663
00:55:24,983 --> 00:55:36,346
[SPEAKER_14]: I will guarantee you that whatever rate, market rate is, the landlord's gonna raise the rent through the roof to make sure they cover that cost.

664
00:55:37,066 --> 00:55:40,407
[SPEAKER_14]: Let that be, that is personal experience.

665
00:55:41,108 --> 00:55:46,894
[SPEAKER_14]: So I just think that we should be very careful when we think of what your predecessor really shared with us.

666
00:55:46,934 --> 00:55:48,696
[SPEAKER_14]: And that keeps resonating to me.

667
00:55:48,736 --> 00:56:04,272
[SPEAKER_14]: We talk about keeping families in Medford, but understanding that the impact, what it, what it really, the benefits from it, how it really is not much of a benefit, um, when it comes to,

668
00:56:05,061 --> 00:56:06,382
[SPEAKER_14]: who has to pick up the slack.

669
00:56:07,082 --> 00:56:14,906
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think that, like Councilor Beall said, this is something that I would be willing to vote for, but it's tonight.

670
00:56:14,966 --> 00:56:29,994
[SPEAKER_14]: But I think that this is a longer discussion and a deeper dive into the numbers to see who it truly impacts and who it could possibly impact negatively if that does happen.

671
00:56:30,034 --> 00:56:31,695
[SPEAKER_14]: So thank you for all your work.

672
00:56:31,715 --> 00:56:32,375
[SPEAKER_14]: I appreciate it.

673
00:56:32,455 --> 00:56:32,735
[SPEAKER_14]: Thanks.

674
00:56:33,155 --> 00:56:33,436
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

675
00:56:33,496 --> 00:56:34,076
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Collins.

676
00:56:35,483 --> 00:56:36,204
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, President Murl.

677
00:56:36,984 --> 00:56:38,786
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you so much for the thorough presentation.

678
00:56:38,886 --> 00:56:43,170
[SPEAKER_02]: I enjoyed looking over these various charts and graphs earlier, so thank you so much.

679
00:56:44,230 --> 00:56:49,815
[SPEAKER_02]: And it's really great to hear about all of the positive changes and increased capacity in the department this year.

680
00:56:49,835 --> 00:56:56,561
[SPEAKER_02]: It's great to see sort of reality meeting the goals for the office, so thank you for steering that ship.

681
00:56:59,092 --> 00:57:16,535
[SPEAKER_02]: I think all of my questions on the overall presentation have been addressed already, but since we're kind of on the topic of the presidential exemption, I'm glad to hear, I mean, it sounds like there's broad consensus that this is not something that we voted on tonight, even if it were, I'd be disinclined to adopt on this timing.

682
00:57:16,996 --> 00:57:24,577
[SPEAKER_02]: I agree, I think that there's a, I think there is a debate to be had on the effect on apartment

683
00:57:25,088 --> 00:57:36,676
[SPEAKER_02]: dwellers, you know, there's the impact of just the raw cost property tax on apartment building owners, and there's the fact that most landlords are reacting to market rate for for rents.

684
00:57:38,057 --> 00:57:42,900
[SPEAKER_02]: But my disinclination doesn't even lie with that conversation, which again we're not having tonight but rather.

685
00:57:45,008 --> 00:57:51,773
[SPEAKER_02]: I think the reason that this comes up all the time in the community is because home values in Medford have gone up so much as they have in the rest of the region.

686
00:57:52,493 --> 00:58:01,019
[SPEAKER_02]: And most of the folks who live in homes that now have higher assessed values than they've ever had before, they didn't move to Medford and buy a mansion or buy a palace.

687
00:58:01,160 --> 00:58:03,621
[SPEAKER_02]: This is just a very desirable place to live in right now.

688
00:58:04,442 --> 00:58:09,626
[SPEAKER_02]: And I'd be very wary of adopting the residential exemption, which would

689
00:58:10,864 --> 00:58:31,750
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, in some cases, marginally decrease tax rates for some owner occupants, but increase them for others, knowing that some of those folks who would see an increased tax bill on their, you know, on their bill are maybe folks who can't afford that or can't afford it any more than the folks below the break-even point because of where the break-even point is given the current market.

690
00:58:35,215 --> 00:58:58,085
[SPEAKER_02]: And I also just, I'm sure you were planning to touch on this, but on the topic also of the small commercial exemption, it seemed to me what I gleaned from your presentation is that this is not an exemption that would, if my understanding is correct, and most of the small business owners in Medford are not property owners, but rather small business tenants, this didn't seem like something that would be advantageous to the folks actually on the ground running small businesses in Medford.

691
00:58:58,145 --> 00:58:59,085
[SPEAKER_02]: Is that accurate?

692
00:58:59,205 --> 00:59:00,286
[SPEAKER_12]: That's correct.

693
00:59:01,146 --> 00:59:03,767
[SPEAKER_12]: Also, the less than a million dollar valuation, that hasn't been updated.

694
00:59:05,248 --> 00:59:11,390
[SPEAKER_12]: We have to be owner occupied and under a million with more than 10 people being employed there.

695
00:59:12,251 --> 00:59:14,151
[SPEAKER_12]: That's not really an equation we see much in the city.

696
00:59:14,691 --> 00:59:19,213
[SPEAKER_02]: Are those eligibility characteristics state imposed?

697
00:59:19,233 --> 00:59:20,033
[SPEAKER_02]: Correct.

698
00:59:20,374 --> 00:59:20,594
[SPEAKER_02]: Got it.

699
00:59:20,934 --> 00:59:24,035
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

700
00:59:24,355 --> 00:59:24,775
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

701
00:59:25,335 --> 00:59:32,158
[SPEAKER_17]: I think much like Councillor Collins, since we did start talking about a residential exemption,

702
00:59:32,995 --> 00:59:43,449
[SPEAKER_17]: Again, we know it's not gonna happen tonight, and it requires a lot of planning, but I just wanted to add my kind of voice and saying I think it's worth exploring.

703
00:59:44,009 --> 00:59:48,275
[SPEAKER_17]: I think the crucial question lies in which, well, essentially,

704
00:59:49,022 --> 01:00:00,807
[SPEAKER_17]: It is pretty unambiguously progressive when it comes to the homeowner side of it, but when we look at renters and apartments, we should explore the consequences of it.

705
01:00:00,827 --> 01:00:03,808
[SPEAKER_17]: I think Councilor Beres makes a good point in that

706
01:00:04,688 --> 01:00:20,875
[SPEAKER_17]: given how unelastic supply and demand can be the markets and might be the one setting the rate, which I think makes a lot of sense given that if it's too expensive here, people can choose to move out of Medford theoretically.

707
01:00:22,119 --> 01:00:33,993
[SPEAKER_17]: But, um, you know, the other economic argument also has seems to have some merit and so we should in the next term, explore, explore this a bit more.

708
01:00:37,263 --> 01:00:41,486
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of this is not in our prerogative.

709
01:00:41,666 --> 01:00:47,430
[SPEAKER_17]: I know Provincetown has an exemption that expands to the full-time renters.

710
01:00:48,171 --> 01:00:50,452
[SPEAKER_17]: They got special permission from the state legislature.

711
01:00:51,393 --> 01:00:54,155
[SPEAKER_17]: Again, that's why it's not in our prerogative.

712
01:00:54,955 --> 01:00:58,517
[SPEAKER_17]: So it is something worth pushing for and exploring, in my opinion.

713
01:01:00,197 --> 01:01:02,818
[SPEAKER_17]: I was curious also about the small commercial exemption.

714
01:01:02,899 --> 01:01:07,140
[SPEAKER_17]: It seemed like the definition was quite specific.

715
01:01:07,600 --> 01:01:16,624
[SPEAKER_17]: And so I was curious as to whether you knew how many people, how many properties would be affected by it, and whether we've ever done it.

716
01:01:16,644 --> 01:01:18,205
[SPEAKER_17]: It doesn't seem familiar to me.

717
01:01:20,633 --> 01:01:24,874
[SPEAKER_12]: I can certainly provide the number of commercial properties under a million dollars.

718
01:01:24,894 --> 01:01:28,356
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't have the labor data for those.

719
01:01:28,576 --> 01:01:30,896
[SPEAKER_12]: I'd have to kind of an individual application basis.

720
01:01:33,877 --> 01:01:34,158
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

721
01:01:35,158 --> 01:01:36,338
[SPEAKER_06]: Any Vice President Behrs?

722
01:01:37,419 --> 01:01:38,119
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you, Madam President.

723
01:01:39,059 --> 01:01:39,859
[SPEAKER_19]: Just two more questions.

724
01:01:39,960 --> 01:01:44,521
[SPEAKER_19]: On the residential exemption, at 35 percent, what was the new rate?

725
01:01:44,921 --> 01:01:45,561
[SPEAKER_19]: Do you have that?

726
01:01:45,581 --> 01:01:46,682
[SPEAKER_19]: Did you calculate that?

727
01:01:46,922 --> 01:01:50,043
[SPEAKER_19]: What's in the PowerPoint, so if you don't have it, totally understand.

728
01:01:52,155 --> 01:01:52,916
[SPEAKER_09]: Excuse me one second.

729
01:02:02,181 --> 01:02:03,122
[SPEAKER_12]: I can get that for you tomorrow.

730
01:02:03,142 --> 01:02:03,722
[SPEAKER_12]: I have it on my desk.

731
01:02:03,762 --> 01:02:04,843
[SPEAKER_12]: I just can't remember exactly what it was.

732
01:02:04,863 --> 01:02:09,146
[SPEAKER_12]: I want to state hearing what exactly, you know, yeah, but I'll send it to you tomorrow.

733
01:02:09,166 --> 01:02:09,466
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

734
01:02:09,766 --> 01:02:14,109
[SPEAKER_19]: And I really just wanted to illustrate the point, like right now we, because we shift,

735
01:02:15,128 --> 01:02:16,549
[SPEAKER_19]: The property tax is a wealth tax.

736
01:02:17,009 --> 01:02:23,813
[SPEAKER_19]: Right now, we have a flat rate wealth tax at two brackets, 1.6% basically, if we adopt everything tonight.

737
01:02:24,233 --> 01:02:26,895
[SPEAKER_19]: For commercial, 0.85 for residential.

738
01:02:27,435 --> 01:02:31,437
[SPEAKER_19]: If we adopted a residential exemption, we'd still have that flat split for the commercial.

739
01:02:31,938 --> 01:02:37,541
[SPEAKER_19]: But instead of being a flat rate, regardless of how wealthy you are, a landlord is, the exemption would basically mean that

740
01:02:38,164 --> 01:02:40,866
[SPEAKER_19]: your rate would be, if you're lower wealth, your rate would be lower.

741
01:02:41,086 --> 01:02:42,667
[SPEAKER_19]: And if you're higher wealth, your rate would be higher.

742
01:02:42,927 --> 01:02:50,373
[SPEAKER_19]: So you'd have a graduated wealth rate for residential property instead of a flat tax, regardless of how much your property is worth.

743
01:02:50,533 --> 01:03:01,601
[SPEAKER_19]: So certainly there could be impacts because some of those high wealth, you know, whoever owns Lumiere or whoever owns the Hanover on Mystic, right?

744
01:03:02,917 --> 01:03:05,878
[SPEAKER_19]: I mean, they own a multi hundred million dollar value property.

745
01:03:05,918 --> 01:03:07,199
[SPEAKER_19]: They're very wealthy landowners.

746
01:03:08,199 --> 01:03:13,461
[SPEAKER_19]: But our tax question could have an indirect impact on the people who rent those apartments, right?

747
01:03:13,501 --> 01:03:15,062
[SPEAKER_19]: So there is an impact there.

748
01:03:15,102 --> 01:03:19,804
[SPEAKER_19]: But my point being that essentially putting a residential exemption is you're creating a graduated wealth tax.

749
01:03:19,864 --> 01:03:24,526
[SPEAKER_19]: So if you're lower wealth, you pay a lower percentage of your property's wealth.

750
01:03:24,606 --> 01:03:26,326
[SPEAKER_19]: And if you're higher wealth, you pay a higher percent.

751
01:03:26,346 --> 01:03:30,288
[SPEAKER_19]: So if we're framing the debate there, there will be individual cases where

752
01:03:31,087 --> 01:03:36,749
[SPEAKER_19]: you know, there's a very, someone who owns a $2 million home and has a very low, you know, uh, fixed income.

753
01:03:36,789 --> 01:03:36,989
[SPEAKER_19]: Right.

754
01:03:37,310 --> 01:03:49,615
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'm not saying that we shouldn't try to factor in for that, but in general, the principle would be instead of if you own a $200,000 home and I think councilor Schafer is trying to shoot, but right now we basically say, if you own a $200,000 home or a $200 million apartment building, you pay the same rate.

755
01:03:55,640 --> 01:03:57,081
[SPEAKER_19]: That's our current tax policy.

756
01:03:57,341 --> 01:04:07,070
[SPEAKER_19]: The residential exemption, to an extent, would be saying maybe we should treat someone who owns a $200,000 home a little differently than someone who owns a $200 million apartment building.

757
01:04:07,991 --> 01:04:08,171
[SPEAKER_12]: Right.

758
01:04:08,591 --> 01:04:13,876
[SPEAKER_12]: It would effectively push the tax rate up a few dollars, but it would give the exemption to those who applied.

759
01:04:13,896 --> 01:04:18,900
[SPEAKER_19]: And the effective tax rate would actually be lower than the current tax rate for low wealth.

760
01:04:19,618 --> 01:04:24,301
[SPEAKER_19]: and higher for high wealth, and the break-even point would basically be where we are now.

761
01:04:24,422 --> 01:04:27,344
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, if you're equating wealth to the value of the property, that would be correct.

762
01:04:27,384 --> 01:04:27,564
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah.

763
01:04:27,804 --> 01:04:28,004
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

764
01:04:28,424 --> 01:04:28,665
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

765
01:04:28,865 --> 01:04:29,085
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

766
01:04:29,525 --> 01:04:29,685
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

767
01:04:30,126 --> 01:04:39,432
[SPEAKER_19]: So I just think, you know, we talk about property, property's an asset, and it's essentially a wealth tax, so, versus the other taxes, we have income and sales taxes, et cetera.

768
01:04:40,193 --> 01:04:41,454
[SPEAKER_19]: So I just think that's helpful to frame the debate.

769
01:04:42,014 --> 01:04:48,719
[SPEAKER_19]: One other thing, I don't know if you've seen it yet, I got an email from someone, I haven't done my research on the legislative back end, but apparently it's either in,

770
01:04:49,627 --> 01:04:55,031
[SPEAKER_19]: a supplemental budget that already passed at the state level or it's in the governor's housing bond bill, and I have to follow up on it.

771
01:04:55,471 --> 01:04:58,993
[SPEAKER_19]: There's some sort of good landlord tax credit that has moved forward.

772
01:04:59,013 --> 01:05:02,735
[SPEAKER_19]: Have you seen anything about that from DLS or anyone you talked to?

773
01:05:02,755 --> 01:05:06,418
[SPEAKER_12]: I saw the October bill that the governor signed.

774
01:05:06,718 --> 01:05:12,182
[SPEAKER_12]: I wasn't aware that that provision was in it, but that would be the one that I would think it would be in, but I can review that.

775
01:05:13,182 --> 01:05:17,065
[SPEAKER_19]: If you could, and I'll do my research too, my understanding of it was basically that

776
01:05:18,088 --> 01:05:21,691
[SPEAKER_19]: you know, if some, if a landlord agreed to rent a unit at an affordable rate, we could.

777
01:05:21,791 --> 01:05:22,912
[SPEAKER_12]: Oh yes, that was the October bill.

778
01:05:23,032 --> 01:05:23,152
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah.

779
01:05:23,212 --> 01:05:23,452
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay.

780
01:05:23,473 --> 01:05:24,593
[SPEAKER_19]: We could offer an exemption.

781
01:05:24,613 --> 01:05:25,094
[SPEAKER_12]: That's correct.

782
01:05:25,474 --> 01:05:31,319
[SPEAKER_19]: Um, what would, would that be a similar to any other exemption where it would just shift the burden within the class?

783
01:05:32,880 --> 01:05:35,603
[SPEAKER_19]: Or would it be an actual credit, like reducing our tax levy?

784
01:05:35,843 --> 01:05:44,230
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, that would be, I believe an exemption, which would come off of the overlay, but I have to check into that, the text of the bill.

785
01:05:44,579 --> 01:05:49,706
[SPEAKER_19]: Because that seems like it might be a policy tool that could mitigate the impact of, say, a residential exemption.

786
01:05:49,727 --> 01:05:52,671
[SPEAKER_19]: Now that I think about that further, it might just

787
01:05:53,664 --> 01:05:55,785
[SPEAKER_12]: adjust the value down, and that would be there.

788
01:05:55,965 --> 01:05:57,445
[SPEAKER_12]: In other words, it would be within the levy.

789
01:05:57,905 --> 01:05:59,746
[SPEAKER_12]: So let me just, I don't wanna say which way it is.

790
01:05:59,846 --> 01:06:00,986
[SPEAKER_12]: So I'll look into that.

791
01:06:01,006 --> 01:06:02,106
[SPEAKER_19]: If it's a shift, it makes sense.

792
01:06:02,146 --> 01:06:03,467
[SPEAKER_19]: If it's a reduction in the levy, that's.

793
01:06:03,687 --> 01:06:05,407
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, well, a reduction in the value.

794
01:06:05,607 --> 01:06:09,929
[SPEAKER_12]: So it's not, I'm sorry, it's not a levy reduction, it's just a reduction in the value, which would push the tax rate up.

795
01:06:10,049 --> 01:06:10,289
[SPEAKER_19]: Okay.

796
01:06:10,509 --> 01:06:10,649
[SPEAKER_19]: Yep.

797
01:06:10,709 --> 01:06:14,310
[SPEAKER_19]: Because that could be another way to mitigate some impacts of what we're talking about.

798
01:06:14,670 --> 01:06:15,110
[SPEAKER_19]: Correct.

799
01:06:15,130 --> 01:06:15,310
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

800
01:06:16,150 --> 01:06:16,931
[SPEAKER_19]: Okay, great.

801
01:06:17,511 --> 01:06:18,411
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you so much, Ted.

802
01:06:18,571 --> 01:06:18,711
[SPEAKER_09]: Yep.

803
01:06:18,771 --> 01:06:19,011
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

804
01:06:19,251 --> 01:06:20,051
[SPEAKER_09]: This is my favorite meeting.

805
01:06:20,071 --> 01:06:20,772
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Madam President.

806
01:06:22,419 --> 01:06:33,623
[SPEAKER_01]: As a lot of people don't know, we have a lot of people that have lived in this community a long time and bought their houses many, many years ago for a lot less than what they're worth now.

807
01:06:34,183 --> 01:06:37,565
[SPEAKER_01]: And many of those people who live in those houses are on fixed incomes.

808
01:06:38,605 --> 01:06:42,166
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think the residential exemption hurts them.

809
01:06:42,626 --> 01:06:47,948
[SPEAKER_01]: And please make people know that we don't collect any more taxes when we do the shift.

810
01:06:48,028 --> 01:06:49,549
[SPEAKER_01]: We still collect the same amount of taxes.

811
01:06:50,229 --> 01:06:52,070
[SPEAKER_01]: We just shift the burden of who pays more.

812
01:06:52,770 --> 01:07:08,320
[SPEAKER_01]: So like Councilor Beall said, you've got someone who lives in a house that may be worth a million and a half, but bought that house 40 years ago for nothing, and now it's a widower living in there on a fixed income and struggling to pay the tax bill.

813
01:07:09,961 --> 01:07:19,046
[SPEAKER_01]: Before we go and do things like that, I think we need to look and see what percentage of people that are living in those higher-end houses, can they afford to

814
01:07:21,026 --> 01:07:22,746
[SPEAKER_01]: paid that shift that will go over to them.

815
01:07:23,607 --> 01:07:28,808
[SPEAKER_01]: So in the future when that comes over, please think hard and fast about how you vote on that.

816
01:07:29,628 --> 01:07:30,008
[SPEAKER_12]: Absolutely.

817
01:07:30,068 --> 01:07:34,910
[SPEAKER_12]: We have a number of individuals in our member community who file for personal exemptions based on their low income.

818
01:07:36,910 --> 01:07:37,670
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councilmember Carrillo.

819
01:07:37,710 --> 01:07:39,071
[SPEAKER_06]: Any further discussion from the Council?

820
01:07:39,391 --> 01:07:42,111
[SPEAKER_06]: I know we likely have at least one member of the public who wants to speak on this.

821
01:07:43,812 --> 01:07:43,972
[SPEAKER_06]: No?

822
01:07:47,063 --> 01:07:47,904
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you want to speak on this?

823
01:07:48,224 --> 01:07:51,027
[SPEAKER_06]: I said I'm sure we have at least one member of the public.

824
01:07:51,107 --> 01:07:58,734
[SPEAKER_09]: I have to start off by saying Castanetti Andrew Cushing Street, East Medford.

825
01:08:09,729 --> 01:08:21,857
[SPEAKER_00]: As Dr. Starelli used to say, you haven't lowered our real estate taxes even once, not even in his lifetime, rest assured, 96 years old, and not in mine either.

826
01:08:22,098 --> 01:08:24,719
[SPEAKER_00]: He says, can you lower it, even for one lousy dollar?

827
01:08:25,500 --> 01:08:26,881
[SPEAKER_00]: Of course, it doesn't happen.

828
01:08:26,981 --> 01:08:30,123
[SPEAKER_00]: It's gone up every single year since before I was born.

829
01:08:31,784 --> 01:08:34,787
[SPEAKER_00]: It seems to me, I'm here for the 19th time,

830
01:08:37,304 --> 01:08:47,773
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm asking you, the city, to adopt and pass the homeowner-occupied real estate tax exemption, known as Mass General Laws, Chapter 59, Section 5C.

831
01:08:49,114 --> 01:09:01,204
[SPEAKER_00]: As you must know, Boston, Cambridge, Malden, Everett, and Chelsea have been doing this for many, many years, and they are still doing it.

832
01:09:02,485 --> 01:09:05,047
[SPEAKER_00]: So, again, I ask, why not here in 02155?

833
01:09:09,029 --> 01:09:19,694
[SPEAKER_00]: From the conversations I was hearing, I wanted to say a few more things, maybe I can catch up later, but I wanted to ask our new real estate tax assessor, who seems very, very competent.

834
01:09:21,574 --> 01:09:29,717
[SPEAKER_00]: And whereas he last worked at the Chelsea Real Estate Tax Department, who does owner-occupied real estate tax exemptions.

835
01:09:30,258 --> 01:09:36,120
[SPEAKER_00]: Three simple questions from Mr. Ted Costigan, Chief City Assessor.

836
01:09:37,660 --> 01:09:44,244
[SPEAKER_00]: First question, did you hear any complaints when you were in Chelsea working about this program?

837
01:09:45,145 --> 01:09:51,429
[SPEAKER_00]: And is Chelsea still doing it?

838
01:09:51,449 --> 01:09:56,472
[SPEAKER_00]: And what are your recommendations going forward to adopt 59-5C in Medford?

839
01:10:00,735 --> 01:10:02,456
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, so the process,

840
01:10:04,382 --> 01:10:10,525
[SPEAKER_12]: is somewhat iterative in that when there's a property that sells or someone buys, they have to be aware of it.

841
01:10:10,605 --> 01:10:13,646
[SPEAKER_12]: So it is certainly an information drive that we need to get out there.

842
01:10:14,747 --> 01:10:18,908
[SPEAKER_12]: It does affect, like we looked at Medford, it's going to affect about 10,000 parcels.

843
01:10:20,129 --> 01:10:25,271
[SPEAKER_12]: We've debated kind of the merits of it back and forth, but it is administratively

844
01:10:27,886 --> 01:10:38,557
[SPEAKER_12]: pretty high level on an assessing office in addition to valuing all the parcels we have to kind of do a double check on making sure that you know constantly checking to make sure if it's rented

845
01:10:39,323 --> 01:10:50,272
[SPEAKER_12]: If someone sells the home, is it truly owner-occupied, checking motor vehicle records, it's a real process to make sure that no one's getting the exemption that shouldn't be.

846
01:10:50,953 --> 01:10:52,734
[SPEAKER_12]: That's probably the number one takeaway.

847
01:10:54,356 --> 01:10:56,437
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think we've talked about the merits back and forth.

848
01:10:56,738 --> 01:10:58,319
[SPEAKER_12]: I'll let that stand.

849
01:10:58,339 --> 01:11:00,421
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

850
01:11:01,842 --> 01:11:07,567
[SPEAKER_00]: And you're going to need two more assistants in your office, I presume, to the owner exemption?

851
01:11:09,227 --> 01:11:13,649
[SPEAKER_12]: So in year one, again, it would be quite difficult.

852
01:11:14,569 --> 01:11:16,990
[SPEAKER_12]: We estimated between 9,000 and 10,000 applications.

853
01:11:17,751 --> 01:11:22,993
[SPEAKER_12]: Medford is a pretty high owner-occupied community.

854
01:11:24,013 --> 01:11:28,275
[SPEAKER_12]: So we had that number right around 65% to 70% of the parcels.

855
01:11:28,915 --> 01:11:34,698
[SPEAKER_12]: So you're talking about roughly 10,000 applications coming in, which all need to be vetted.

856
01:11:37,748 --> 01:11:50,377
[SPEAKER_00]: Because across the street from him Cushing Street is a two family that's owned by an absentee owner who lives in Winchester down the street, three houses away so no one was in Beaumont, and another one.

857
01:11:52,259 --> 01:11:58,003
[SPEAKER_00]: And they don't live in the houses so therefore I consider them commercial enterprises they're running it as a business.

858
01:11:58,663 --> 01:12:03,804
[SPEAKER_00]: At $3,000 a month rent, there's five bedrooms upstairs, just on one flat, mind you.

859
01:12:04,164 --> 01:12:06,185
[SPEAKER_00]: Five different cars, and every month it changes.

860
01:12:06,245 --> 01:12:09,405
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm not sure if it's like a Uber type hotel, so to speak.

861
01:12:10,085 --> 01:12:11,406
[SPEAKER_00]: And it changes a lot.

862
01:12:12,046 --> 01:12:13,446
[SPEAKER_00]: So they're running it as a business.

863
01:12:14,006 --> 01:12:20,548
[SPEAKER_00]: And they would get slapped with our savings, because the city's still going to get the $130 million tax levy thereabouts, period.

864
01:12:21,548 --> 01:12:26,869
[SPEAKER_00]: So if we get the tax savings as unoccupied, and that's been the backbone of the city.

865
01:12:28,890 --> 01:12:31,692
[SPEAKER_00]: They've carried this weight for 1900.

866
01:12:32,453 --> 01:12:37,236
[SPEAKER_00]: And I don't want to see anyone see an increase, to be honest with you, including the rentals.

867
01:12:39,378 --> 01:12:48,165
[SPEAKER_00]: And getting back to what Mr. Beers made a comment about, I'm not sure what it was exactly, but it triggered this in my mind.

868
01:12:52,783 --> 01:13:00,907
[SPEAKER_00]: It is true, if we adopt that the full 35% exemption, which is allowed by law, without asking for special exemption, like Somerville has tried.

869
01:13:01,868 --> 01:13:06,550
[SPEAKER_00]: But if we get the full 35, they say go for the full 35 or it's not worth it, a full one with 5%.

870
01:13:07,310 --> 01:13:18,055
[SPEAKER_00]: But if you get the full 35 or even less, on a $200,000 condo, and you probably can find one, their $4,000 tax bill would go down to like $1,000.

871
01:13:18,176 --> 01:13:20,917
[SPEAKER_00]: That doesn't seem fair to me.

872
01:13:22,407 --> 01:13:30,852
[SPEAKER_00]: So I think the law is flawed, because if you had a $2 million house, you're going to see an increase after the $930,000.

873
01:13:31,492 --> 01:13:45,701
[SPEAKER_00]: So I think this law is flawed on a state level, because every single owner occupied should get

874
01:13:46,785 --> 01:13:53,766
[SPEAKER_00]: the same dollar value of savings, no matter if you have a $100,000 pad or a $5 million mansion in Mystic Lakes.

875
01:13:54,486 --> 01:13:57,647
[SPEAKER_00]: Everyone should get the same, it might be $1,000, $2,000, or $3,000.

876
01:13:58,627 --> 01:14:02,248
[SPEAKER_00]: And it should be a simple mathematical computation.

877
01:14:02,288 --> 01:14:09,709
[SPEAKER_00]: I didn't go to MIT, but if you take whatever it is, it's a huge number, 35% of the valuation.

878
01:14:09,729 --> 01:14:12,609
[SPEAKER_00]: It's like a trillion dollars or something like that.

879
01:14:12,729 --> 01:14:13,490
[SPEAKER_00]: It's really big.

880
01:14:13,910 --> 01:14:14,750
[SPEAKER_00]: And if you divide it by,

881
01:14:16,404 --> 01:14:21,826
[SPEAKER_00]: The total amount of all owner-occupied will come out to a set dollar amount.

882
01:14:22,686 --> 01:14:23,807
[SPEAKER_00]: That would make sense to me.

883
01:14:24,847 --> 01:14:30,329
[SPEAKER_00]: Instead of some person saving half on the tax bill from $4,000 to $2,000, the other ones

884
01:14:33,741 --> 01:14:34,963
[SPEAKER_00]: It just doesn't make sense.

885
01:14:35,223 --> 01:14:37,626
[SPEAKER_00]: So I can't fight City Hall and win.

886
01:14:37,906 --> 01:14:40,088
[SPEAKER_00]: How am I going to fight the state and get them to correct that?

887
01:14:40,849 --> 01:14:42,311
[SPEAKER_00]: And he can do it for me right now.

888
01:14:42,832 --> 01:14:49,960
[SPEAKER_00]: He knows the valuation of the 35% of the valuation and divide it by how many owner-occupies there are, and that would be the amount, wouldn't it?

889
01:14:50,650 --> 01:14:53,831
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you had a calculator that was that big, you could do that for me right now.

890
01:14:54,531 --> 01:14:57,071
[SPEAKER_00]: But I want to thank you because you seem very efficient.

891
01:14:57,811 --> 01:15:00,972
[SPEAKER_00]: How long did you work in the Chelsea operation?

892
01:15:00,992 --> 01:15:04,573
